To terminate a C program, you can use the exit() function. The exit() function takes an integer as an argument, which is the status code returned to the operating system. For example, you can use the following code to terminate a program with a status code of 0:

```c
#include <stdlib.h>

int main() {
    exit(0);
    return 0;
}
```

Alternatively, you can use the return statement to terminate a program. The return statement returns the value specified as the status code. For example, you can use the following code to terminate a program with a status code of 1:

```c
#include <stdlib.h>

int main() {
    return 1;
}
```

You can also use the exit() function with a string argument to print a message before terminating the program. For example:

```c
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    printf("Goodbye, world!\n");
    exit("Goodbye, world!");
    return 0;
}
```

In this example, the program prints the message "Goodbye, world!" and then terminates with a status code of 0.
